segments.text: I had compulsory chapel every Sunday morning.
Everyone had to go.
And it's all the students, even the seniors?
Did you ever have any visiting speakers?
Yes, there were all visiting speakers.
Of course, I don't remember any of them.
Where would they speak, in Guyon Hall?
In Guyon.
They had a regular church, sort of a church service.
They had a song service and preaching.
Okay, let me clarify.
You had to, I believe they kind of rotated among the local, probably Bryan ministers for that services.
Well, they'd bring others in from different places.
I don't know where they got them all, but there's always one there.
What I was wondering is, did they ever have a,
say, a foreign traveler or some dignitary to come and speak to the students?
No, it was always a religious nature on Sunday morning.
They had these other things you're talking about during the week.
That's what I was meaning.
During the week they'd have them in there.
They were not compulsory.
You could go if you liked.
Did the cadet officers have any privileges that were not
available to the other cadets?
Well, just regular senior privileges.
Of course, not having been a senior officer, I mean, I was in the civilian corps then.
I don't know about that, except as a freshman it always looked to me like they had the gravy.
Did you have any favorite instructors
Well, I liked Smith.
I've forgotten his name.
He taught calculus.
Probably been in the Robert F. Cuball Ritchie.
He was head of the physics, no, CE department.
And Bolton was head of the electrical department.
General Love was one of the civil engineering professors.
He usually had charge of the summer practice, CE practice.
You called him General.
Was he a retired military man?
I don't know where he got that name.
He kept a box of chalk on his desk, and if he ever saw you nodding or looking out the window, he'd let you have a piece of chalk right in your face.
Pretty good aim, huh?
Yeah.
One of the things that I think sets Texas A&M apart from other schools is the number of traditions that are carried on from year to year by the students.
And today we have the big bonfire that's in some controversy, the tradition of silver taps, the annual muster on April 21st.
Did you have any of these when you were there as a student?
That's one thing that made me love A&M was all of those things.
It meant so much to all of us.
It's just like one big family, really.
Did you build a bonfire all four of the years you were there?
And everybody worked on it?
Yeah.
And what about a muster?
Did you have a special ceremony of some sort on the 21st of April?
I don't remember any on the campus.
We've had musters since we got out, of course.
We always had to go to Yale practice.
You had to attend Yale practice.
That was required attendance.
Yeah.
Were there any girls in any of the classes while you were there?
There were one or two girls who were daughters of some of the professors, but they were not on a full-time basis.
They were just taking the course now and then.
And there were a few women, girls, that were secretaries in the administration building, but there were very few.
Did any of them take any courses?
I don't remember of any.
They more than likely were, what, residents in Bryant?
Yeah.
They would ride the trolley back and forth to campus.
Did that trolley have a pretty convenient schedule that you could get in and out without any?
Yeah.
undue complications.
You had a little trouble getting on sometimes.
You'd probably have to hang on outside.
A lot more people wanting to go than it was room, huh?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
In checking over the longhorn from your senior year,
There was an indication that you were a casual, and that meant that you were not in the military.
Did they ever use the term non-reg?
No, not in the casuals.
We were called casuals.
And you didn't have to wear any kind of uniform at that point?
No, we were entirely out of the military.
It had nothing to do with it at all.
point later on where somebody told me yesterday that even though he was not in the military his senior year, he had to wear a uniform.
It had an NM on his collar that said non-military.
No.
No, that wasn't true.
He just wore regular civilian clothes all the time.
Do you have any recollection as to how they came up with the term casual?
No, I don't know where that
Other than it was casual clothes that you wore, perhaps.
I always took it to mean that you were a casualty.
I see.
That's really the way it started.
It was for boys that were unable physically to participate in the military, had some injury or something happened to them.
That's always what I thought it was.
That might not be right.
Also, you remember the Gold Brickers Club.
Yeah.
What was that?
Well, I didn't belong to that.
I don't know.
In fact, I didn't belong to any club except the Panhandle Club and the C.E.
Club.
Were you aware of the existence of the Gold Brickers Club?
Oh, yeah.
What was it?
Well, I don't remember.
I don't know.
I didn't know anything about it.
I had my own ideas.
Well, today a Gold Bricker is somebody who's always trying to get out and do some work.
Well, of course, that's what the idea was.
I mean, that's what it conveyed to me.
Okay.
When you graduated then in the spring of 22, did you have a job lined up the time you graduated?
What was that?
It was assistant city engineer in Breckenridge, Texas.
Is that suburb kind of San Antonio?
No, Breckenridge in Stevens County.
Stevens County.
Close to Abilene.
I was thinking of Breckenridge Park in San Antonio.
No, in addition to my regular CE course, I took a course in highway engineering.
And I got the job with a firm, Hawley and Sands, who operated in Fort Worth.
And they had a resident man in Breckenridge.
And they were getting ready to do the first paving that went into Breckenridge, Texas.
And when he saw on my record that I had done some special work in paving, asphalt paving, he needed an asphalt man.
And that's how come me to get the job.
I designed the first asphalt paving that went into Breckenridge.
However, we paved the main street with brick and put in the first sewer system.
Was that, how was the brick laid?
Was it herringbone or just?
No, it was, I don't know what you call it.
It wasn't herringbone.
We put out about an eight-inch concrete base and put about
couple of inches of sand on it, laid the brick on that, and it was all done by hand.
Not much other way to lay brick is.
Did you have reinforcing steel in the concrete base?
Yeah.
Were you involved in the design of that part of the street too?
Well, I did a lot of the drafting on it.
I didn't do any of the design on that, no.
But then you say you were involved in the design of the sewer system?
The sewer system and the asphalt.
How long did you stay in Breckenridge then?
I believe I was there a little over a year, and then I went to work for Pittsburgh Testing Laboratories in San Antonio.
At that time they had a contract to test all the
pavement that went down in San Antonio, about four or five different paving companies operating there.
And I had a laboratory and it was my job to take samples, daily samples of their work.
This was to make sure that they were using the Check it to see if it was within specifications.
Specified materials for the pavement.
Check the amount of asphalt that was in it, percentage of asphalt.
character asphalt, and also the gravel and metal base that went into it.
And how long did you stay at that then?
Oh, a couple of years, I guess.
And then I had a chance to go to Shackleford County, but Albany, Texas is a
County, Cedar-Sapford County, as an assistant county engineer.
At that time, they were doing a lot of highway work.
And I was assistant to the county engineer there.
We built some roads north of Bracken Ridge and east toward Caddo.
This would be asphalt roads.
Asphalt roads.
Within the county.
Uh-huh.
They were just county roads.
And we were working for the county commissioner.
But we found out that the county judge and one of the commissioners and the contractor had a thing going.
And we were on just a month-to-month basis.
We didn't have a contract to do the engineering, just working for them by the month.
The judge called us in and told us he wanted us to favor the contractor in certain aspects.
In fact, he wanted us to take an inspector off the concrete bridge.
Said he thought we could tell whether it was concrete or not when it took the forms off.
And several things that he instructed us to do, and we told him we couldn't do that.
And he said, well,
You boys stick with us, and we'll have you making $1,000 a month right along.
As you come back in a few days, and he asked us then at the end of the three days, and we told him we were still of the same opinion.
He said, well, get your stuff and get out of the courthouse.
So that ended that.
I had just bought a lot and built a home, furnished it, settled down.
This was in Albany.
No, in Breckenridge.
In Breckenridge, yeah.
And then I went to work the next week, I guess it was, for Texas Carbon Industries.
They had a carbon plant in Breckenridge making carbon black, which at that time was pretty much in demand for automobile tires, Victrola records, and printer's ink, and such as that.
And I went from there.
over to Albany working for an oil company in petroleum engineering construction.
Built some gasoline plants, repressor plants, recycling plants.
What company was this?
It was an independent company, Rosier and Pendleton.
They've since gone out of existence.
Just a couple of fellows that came out of the army and
Struck it lucky and got a lease over there and built up quite a thing.
It was quite an organization for about twenty-five years.
Did they sell out to somebody else?
No, we finally exhausted the supply.
It was sand production, sand lenses, and it's kind of like this Ogallala water formation here.
It just had so much in it and we got it all out and that was it.
And then we moved to Lubbock from there.
My wife had some farms up in this area, Castro and Bailey and Hockley County.
When was that that you moved to Lubbock?
That was 1949.
And that's what I've been doing since then, looking after the farms.
What's your principal crop then?
Or crops, I guess.
Well, I guess maize, probably, and corn now.
We've raised lots of corn the last few years.
But we raised maize and wheat, sugar beets, cotton, corn, and some soybeans.
Has this been a gradual change, going into different commodities?
Well, no, not especially.
Of course, when we first started out, there wasn't much irrigation.
Irrigation was just getting going.
We drilled a bunch of wells and gradually got into different phases.
Of course, within the last ten years, sugar beets have been in.
We didn't have any sugar beets early, because they built that plant at Hereford.
But the main thing this year, nearly everything's in corn and maize.
We had some wheat and a little cotton, not much cotton.
Did the sugar beet plant come in and did somebody decide it was a good area to grow sugar beets and encourage the production and build the plant, or did the plant come first?
Some outfit in Denver, Holly, Holly Sugar Corporation,
They put a plant in at Hereford.
Of course, they made us help pay for it.
They took out a dollar or two dollars a ton out of every ton of beets that went in there to help pay for the plant.
But our main crop the last two years has been maize and corn.
Did you raise any cattle along with the
No.
We've had a few cattle along, but never over 40 head, I guess.
Some of the farms had grass on them, and of course we'd graze the wheat and things like that.
After you've combined the wheat, you graze the... Well, we graze it after it's planted, planted about
middle of October, and you can turn on it about, oh, sometime before Christmas and leave them on there until March.
And of course, when the maize is harvested, turn them on the maize stalks.
Well, in other words, you raised the wheat as a winter grazing crop rather than as a grain.
No, it was raised principally for harvest.
But the grazing was just incidental.
But so the grazing was prior to the harvest or after?
Oh, yeah, before the harvest.
Before the harvest.
Yeah.
Yeah, before it heads.
When it starts to head, you have to take off of it before the boot starts.
The boot is what the head grows in.
You can take it off, take off the grazing before that.
It was more or less incidental.
Um.
Would you say then that irrigation has been one of the big developments in the last 25, 30 years in the farming of this area?
Yeah.
Of course, it started way back in the, well, I think the first well drilled up here in Plainview around 1911.
But there wasn't very much irrigation done before 1935.
Most of the early irrigation was what, with windmills?
No, it was all- Gasoline pumps?
With irrigation pumps.
The first irrigation out at Portales, when we lived out there, there was some irrigation.
That was back in 1907 and eight, nine.
But at that time, they had no equipment to lift the water.
They'd dig a pit.

down twenty-five feet deep and about ten feet square and it set an ordinary centrifugal pump down there because it wouldn't pick the water up and put the engine up on top and belt driven down through there and that centrifugal pump would throw the water out of that hole but of course then later sometime in the twenties some man designed a
the modern irrigation pumps.
That's when irrigation really got started.
Of course, even then they didn't have gear heads.
They drove their pumps by a belt, a long flat belt hooked onto an engine sitting out ten or fifteen feet away.
But now the engines are all direct connected to a gear head, which is not the same as a differential on a car, but it has a big gear and a little gear on the engine, kind of like a car differential.
And the motor is direct connected to it.
When you came out to Lubbock to sort of take over the farms, did you sever all connections with Rosser and Pendleton?
Yes.
I did some work here for Coleman Hazy and some engineering over at Sudan.
Put in the water system over there and a sewer system in Sudan in 19well, that was before
That was back in the 30s, so I was working then for the city of Sudan.
But after I came here, I worked for Coleman Hazy.
We did some work at Post and Summit, Littlefield, and Bevel Land, Graham, paving and sewer work, things like that.
But I was just on a salary with Coleman Hazy, Hazy and Green.
Are you doing any kind of engineering at the moment?
Oh, no.
No, I haven't done any of that in 10 years.
Well, I mean, there have been a lot of developments along the line there.
Oh, yeah.
That you'd have to keep up with.
Quite different now.
Yeah, I'd have to go to school again to go back in the oil field.
They've learned things that we didn't know about.
What about sewer systems and paving?
Well, it hasn't changed a whole lot, basically.
Well, I was talking with a highwayman yesterday, and he said, as far as he was concerned, the principal development in highways has been the computerization of design work.
Yeah.
I imagine so, of course.
I know nothing about that.
I don't have any conception of what a computer is.
You said that the products which they use today is not drastically different from what they were using forty years ago to build roads.
That's right.
Although they build them wider and longer.
Of course, back in the early twenties in the summertime while I was going to A&M, I worked for the highway department on highways up around Amarillo.
and all the material then was hauled in by teams, mule teams, horse teams, and everything was done by hand except the hauling of the gravel.
They used Fresnos with three mules hitched to a Fresno to do the dirt work where they do it now with all the machines.
Basically, it was the same then as now.
They put on a 10 or 12 inch base, top it off with some asphalt mixture of some kind.
That was it.
Either that or concrete.
They'd been doing that for a long time.
Yeah, they'd been doing concrete a long time.
There wasn't too much of it done, though, up until the late 20s.
Have you been involved in any kind of social or fraternal activities or any political activities?
No.
No, I haven't been in politics at all.
Oh, we belong to little groups here, Sunday schools and church groups and occasional bridge group.
Nothing of any consequence.
And I haven't been going to A&M Club.
I don't know that I've ever been to it here.
I used to go in Houston, San Antonio.
And I belonged to the Agriculture Club here for a while, but I haven't been active in that for 10 or 15 years.
I never was much of a joiner.
Well, you have to have some of that joining characteristic to belong and continue activities.
Most of our activities have been in connection with the church and Sunday school.
Well, not everybody can be participating in everything.
